EVED=0.5, NOT_ACHIEVED/CANCELED=0.0); UNDERCOMMIT true positive if plan had spare capacity AND all commits ACHIEVED; REPEATED_CARRY_FORWARD true positive if the flagged commit's outcome is NOT_ACHIEVED or CANCELED; BLOCKED_CRITICAL true positive if the flagged commit's outcome is NOT_ACHIEVED; SCOPE_VOLATILITY true positive if any commit outcome is NOT_ACHIEVED, (4) aggregate per-signal-type confusion matrix → precision/recall/F1. Output results to build/eval-results/replay-benchmark.json via Jackson ObjectMapper. Since this is a pure unit test with synthetic data, setup should always succeed. Use Assumptions.assumeTrue() only as a defensive guard.\n\n2. `docs/eval-results.md` — Markdown document: overview of eval approach (rules-based + LLM-augmented), per-capability eval summary table (commit-draft-assist: 12 cases, commit-lint: 6 cases, rcdo-suggest: 10 cases, risk-signal: 8 cases, reconcile-assist: 8 cases, rag-query: 8 cases, what-if: 8 cases — these counts match the actual files in backend/src/test/resources/eval/*/cases.json), historical replay benchmark section with metrics table (signal type / # predicted / # actual / true positives / precision / recall / F1) showing placeholder values to be filled by running ./gradlew evalTest, and \"How to run\" section explaining ./gradlew test (unit tests) and ./gradlew evalTest (eval tests, requires OPENROUTER_API_KEY). Note: the benchmark writes machine-readable results to build/eval-results/replay-benchmark.json; this markdown doc is the human-readable companion with placeholder tables that document the approach.",
